DNA is also damaged because of errors during its replication. A variety of different DNA repair pathways have been reported that include direct reversal, base excision repair, nucleotide excision repair, photoreactivation, bypass, double-strand break repair pathway, and mismatch repair pathway." description: "Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the error-free repair of a double-strand break in DNA in which the broken DNA molecule is repaired using homologous sequences." [GOC:dph, GOC:jp, GOC:tb]
name: regulation of double-strand break repair via homologous recombination

description: "Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus. The process begins with detection of the stimulus by a cell and ends with a change in state or activity or the cell." [GOC:bf, GOC:jl]
name: cellular response to stimulus

description: "The synthesis of the large ribosomal RNA (rRNA) transcript which encodes several rRNAs, e.g. in mammals 28S, 18S and 5.8S, from a nuclear DNA template transcribed by RNA polymerase I." [GOC:jl, GOC:txnOH, ISBN:0321000382]
name: nucleolar large rRNA transcription by RNA polymerase I

description: "Any process involved in forming the mature 5' end of a non-coding RNA molecule." [GOC:mah]
name: ncRNA 5'-end processing

description: "A signaling process that controls cell cycle progression in response to changes in DNA structure by monitoring the integrity of the DNA during mitosis. The DNA integrity checkpoint begins with detection of DNA damage, defects in DNA structure or DNA replication, and ends with signal transduction." [GOC:mtg_cell_cycle]
name: mitotic DNA integrity checkpoint signaling

description: "Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of substances, carried out by individual cells." [GOC:mah]
name: regulation of cellular catabolic process

description: "Splicing of tRNA substrates via recognition of the folded RNA structure that brings the 5' and 3' splice sites into proximity and cleavage of the RNA at both the 3' and 5' splice sites by an endonucleolytic mechanism, followed by ligation of the exons." [GOC:krc, ISBN:0879695897, PMID:9582290]
name: tRNA splicing, via endonucleolytic cleavage and ligation

description: "The series of molecular signals in which an intracellular signal is conveyed to trigger the apoptotic death of a cell. The pathway is induced in response to a stimulus indicating endoplasmic reticulum (ER) stress, and ends when the execution phase of apoptosis is triggered. ER stress usually results from the accumulation of unfolded or misfolded proteins in the ER lumen." [GOC:mah, GOC:mtg_apoptosis, PMID:18701708]
name: intrinsic apoptotic signaling pathway in response to endoplasmic reticulum stress

description: "Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of mitotic sister chromatid separation." [GOC:TermGenie, PMID:1846086]
name: positive regulation of mitotic sister chromatid separation

description: "A signal transduction process that contributes to a DNA replication checkpoint, that prevents the initiation of nuclear division until DNA replication is complete, thereby ensuring that progeny inherit a full complement of the genome." [GOC:curators, GOC:rn, PMID:11728327, PMID:12537518]
name: DNA replication checkpoint signaling

description: "The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of carbohydrates, any of a group of organic compounds based of the general formula Cx(H2O)y." [ISBN:0198506732]
name: carbohydrate biosynthetic process

description: "Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of a process involved in the formation, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of cell structures, including the plasma membrane and any external encapsulating structures such as the cell wall and cell envelope." [GOC:ai]
name: positive regulation of cellular component organization

description: "Any process involved in the development or functioning of the immune system, an organismal system for calibrated responses to potential internal or invasive threats." [GO_REF:0000022, GOC:add]
name: immune system process

description: "The conversion of DNA-damage induced single-stranded gaps into large molecular weight DNA after replication. Includes pathways that remove replication-blocking lesions in conjunction with DNA replication." [GOC:elh]
name: postreplication repair

description: "Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of transcription of nuclear large rRNA mediated by RNA polymerase I." [GOC:sart, GOC:TermGenie]
name: regulation of transcription of nucleolar large rRNA by RNA polymerase I

description: "The process in which an existing DNA strand is extended by activities including the addition of nucleotides to the 3' end of the strand, complementary to an existing template, as part of DNA replication." [GOC:mah, ISBN:071673706X, ISBN:0815316194]
name: DNA strand elongation involved in DNA replication

description: "The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of GMP, guanosine monophosphate." [ISBN:0198506732]
name: GMP biosynthetic process

description: "Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of initiation of DNA-dependent DNA replication; the process in which DNA becomes competent to replicate. In eukaryotes, replication competence is established in early G1 and lost during the ensuing S phase." [GOC:mah]
name: regulation of DNA-templated DNA replication initiation

description: "Any nuclear DNA replication that is involved in a mitotic cell cycle." [GO_REF:0000060, GOC:TermGenie]
name: mitotic DNA replication

description: "Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of proteins by the translation of mRNA in a mitochondrion." [GOC:mah]
name: positive regulation of mitochondrial translation

description: "Removal of a DNA interstrand crosslink (a covalent attachment of DNA bases on opposite strands of the DNA) and restoration of the DNA. DNA interstrand crosslinks occur when both strands of duplex DNA are covalently tethered together (e.g. by an exogenous or endogenous agent), thus preventing the strand unwinding necessary for essential DNA functions such as transcription and replication." [GOC:vw, PMID:16464006, PMID:22064477]
name: interstrand cross-link repair

description: "Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of chromosome segregation, the process in which genetic material, in the form of chromosomes, is organized and then physically separated and apportioned to two or more sets." [GOC:ai]
name: positive regulation of chromosome segregation

description: "An interaction between two organisms living together in more or less intimate association. The term host is used for the larger (macro) of the two members of a symbiosis; the various forms of symbiosis include parasitism, commensalism and mutualism." [GOC:cc]
name: biological process involved in interaction with host

description: "Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of stem cell population maintenance." [GOC:obol]
name: regulation of stem cell population maintenance

description: "Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of chromosome condensation." [GO_REF:0000058, GOC:bhm, GOC:TermGenie, PMID:17268547]
name: positive regulation of chromosome condensation

description: "Any process that modulates the establishment or extent of the mitochondrial membrane potential, the electric potential existing across the mitochondrial membrane arising from charges in the membrane itself and from the charges present in the media on either side of the membrane." [GOC:ai]
name: regulation of mitochondrial membrane potential

description: "Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of telomerase activity, the catalysis of the reaction: deoxynucleoside triphosphate + DNA(n) = diphosphate + DNA(n+1)." [GOC:ai]
name: positive regulation of telomerase activity

description: "The cell cycle process by which a cell in G1 phase commits to S phase." [GOC:mtg_cell_cycle]
name: cell cycle G1/S phase transition

description: "The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of constituent RNAs and proteins to form the large ribosomal subunit." [GOC:jl, PMID:30467428]
name: ribosomal large subunit assembly

description: "The chemical reactions and pathways involving polyprenols, prenols with more than 4 isoprenoid residues, which may be all-trans, or a mixture of cis and trans." [PMID:11108713]
name: polyprenol metabolic process

description: "The repair of a double-strand break in DNA in which the two broken ends are rejoined with little or no sequence complementarity. Information at the DNA ends may be lost due to the modification of broken DNA ends. This term covers instances of separate pathways, called classical (or canonical) and alternative nonhomologous end joining (C-NHEJ and A-NHEJ). These in turn may further branch into sub-pathways, but evidence is still unclear." [GOC:rph, PMID:10827453, PMID:24837021]
name: double-strand break repair via nonhomologous end joining

description: "The chemical reactions and pathways involving a ribonucleoside diphosphate, a compound consisting of a nucleobase linked to a ribose sugar esterified with diphosphate on the sugar." [GOC:go_curators, ISBN:0198506732]
name: ribonucleoside diphosphate metabolic process

description: "Any process that decreases the frequency, rate or extent of cell communication. Cell communication is the process that mediates interactions between a cell and its surroundings. Encompasses interactions such as signaling or attachment between one cell and another cell, between a cell and an extracellular matrix, or between a cell and any other aspect of its environment." [GOC:dph, GOC:tb]
name: negative regulation of cell communication

description: "Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of endopeptidase activity, the endohydrolysis of peptide bonds within proteins." [GOC:ai, GOC:hjd]
name: regulation of endopeptidase activity

description: "The chemical reactions and pathways by which individual cells transform chemical substances." [GOC:go_curators]
name: cellular metabolic process

description: "Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a chemical stimulus." [GOC:mah]
name: cellular response to chemical stimulus

description: "The biological process whose specific outcome is the progression of a multicellular organism over time from an initial condition (e.g. a zygote or a young adult) to a later condition (e.g. a multicellular animal or an aged adult)." [GOC:dph, GOC:ems, GOC:isa_complete, GOC:tb]
name: multicellular organism development

description: "Mitotic bipolar spindle assembly begins with spindle microtubule nucleation from the separated spindle pole body, includes spindle elongation during prometaphase, and is complete when all kinetochores are stably attached the spindle, and the spindle assembly checkpoint is satisfied." [GOC:tb, GOC:vw]
name: mitotic spindle assembly

description: "Any process that increases the rate, frequency or extent of release of cytochrome c from mitochondria, the process in which cytochrome c is enabled to move from the mitochondrial intermembrane space into the cytosol, which is an early step in apoptosis and leads to caspase activation." [GOC:BHF, GOC:dph, GOC:mtg_apoptosis, GOC:tb]
name: positive regulation of release of cytochrome c from mitochondria

description: "The cellular process in which spindle microtubules become physically associated with the proteins making up the kinetochore complex in mitosis." [GOC:ai, GOC:clt, GOC:dph, GOC:tb, PMID:26258632, PMID:26705896]
name: attachment of mitotic spindle microtubules to kinetochore

description: "Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of mitochondrial outer membrane permeabilization involved in apoptotic signaling pathway." [GOC:BHF, GOC:mtg_apoptosis, GOC:TermGenie]
name: regulation of mitochondrial outer membrane permeabilization involved in apoptotic signaling pathway
